            "answer_text": "I live just outside of Philadelphia and used to feed all types of birds from feeders in my backyard, however, I also scattered seed on my back patio area for the pigeons, cowbirds and other large birds that couldn\u2019t utilize the feeders. This, of course, meant I also fed the squirrels who helped themselves to the \u201cfeast\u201d dropped on the ground. What I never expected was to step out my back door one morning and find two mallard ducks\u2014a male and a female\u2014trying to scrape up the food from the pavement. They saw me and flew away. But the next morning, they were back. I kept up with the feeders, and sprinkling the seed on the ground, but now I also placed a bowl of seed as well as a bowl of water at the edge of the grass about 15 ft from my door. The ducks (I started calling her Momma Duck and never really gave the handsome, silky green-necked male a name) quickly learned the bowls were theirs and they came every morning. Then twice a day\u2014morning and evening. I had no idea where they came from since there was no body of water anywhere around that I could think of, but it became obvious, they weren\u2019t going away. They were my twice-a-day visitors and I found myself looking forward to their visits. As days and weeks passed, they let me get closer, and I found it both humorous and chivalrous that the male would \u201cstand guard\u201d while Momma Duck ate and drank and only when she was finished would he dine. Often, they would hang out in my back yard, pecking at the grass, or just \u201changing out\u201d for sometimes up to an hour before heading off to parts unknown. As cool weather set in, they finally departed and I wished them well, glad to have been able to spend time with them, however limited. Until the next summer, when they returned\u2026 and then the next\u2026 Although after the third summer I noticed the male was different and much more hesitant to approach, Momma Duck was the same and she permitted me to get within almost touching distance. Occasionally the bowls would be empty\u2014or too empty for their liking\u2014and Momma began coming directly up to my back door and quacking until I came to fill the bowls. Once I opened the door, she would waddle almost directly next to me toward the bowls while I intoned the words \u201cMomma Duck\u201d over and over so she learned to recognize my voice. If my husband or one of my friends tried to come out with me, both ducks grew nervous and backed away, but once I started the \u201cMomma Duck\u201d sound, she would come toward me and escort me toward the bowls. This continued for six or seven years and then, one summer, Momma appeared alone. I called her by name as I placed the bowls and she ate and drank, and then she was gone. And I never saw either of them again. ",
