            "answer_text": "I assume so. My cockatiel lets me manhandle him. No need to extend a finger if I don't want to. I just put my hand over his back and pick him up. Anyone else puts a finger near him and he's immediately defensive and nips at their hand. So, at least one bird can recognize me. He also knows my voice, and will respond to it if he can hear me from the other room. He won't do that for other people. And oddly enough, my cough and sniffle. If I sniffle loud or cough while coming up the stairs to my apartment, he'll respond. Doesn't make a peep when anyone else comes up the stairs. Also, any time I fart in the middle of the night, he typically lets out a little chirp. That always amuses me in the middle of the night. \u201cbrrap.\u201d \u201cpeep!\u201d I also took some fledgling crows out of the yard to the Audubon society after one of them died and my roommate kept threatening to throw them all in the street. That flock of crows went ballistic every time I stepped outside the house for awhile. Never did that for my roommate or anyone else visiting. ",
