                "name": "Joe Asher",
                "href": "/profile/Joe-Asher-4"
            },
            "answer_text": "Definitely. There are many, many experiments confirming this. Look up \u201ccrows hold grudges\u201d to find articles on crows that were abused by people wearing a particular mask to find out if they could recognise the \u2018face\u2019 when seen again. The crows then for 5 years attaked people wearing the same mask in the area. It wasn\u2019t even just the crows that were abused, their offspring and other crows joined in too showing that they can disseminate information about individual humans. In a different experiment pigeons were fed by one person and then chased by another. Neither wore masks but after a few days they swapped clothing and stopped chasing/feeding them, to see if the pigeons recognized the clothes or the human wearing them. They ignored the clothing and were still friendly to the feeder person but vary cautious about the chaser. They can definitely recognize individual humans. ",
